76561198041519091,Recommended,257830,8064857,"Posted: 16 December, 2013",all,WhitePaw2011,"I quickly snapped up Violett and eagerly jumped into the game once it installed. I have to admit feeling a little lost at the beginning as there is no spoon feeding. You are plunged straight into an environment that encourages you to explore. I normally enjoy these sort of games but I find Violett frustrates me more than entertains me. I'm a good portion of my way in and I no longer have the satisfaction of solving a puzzle or the excitement of a new location.Graphically it is interesting and the imaginative game world, inspired by Alice in Wonderland, certainly adds a new dimension. Music is okay and helps set the atmosphere. But something is missing, something just doesn't quite gel.Most of the puzzles do make sense in their own, sometime surreal, way although I do find myself randomly clicking on things without a sense of direction when I'm stuck. Other times I've missed important clues that blended a little too well with the background or solved something by accident without really knowing what I did. A few puzzles were simple enough to solve but tedious to execute and my only satisfaction in completing them was I didn't have to do it again.Maybe part of what is missing, for me at least, is some sort of feedback mechanism. I feel detached from what is going on in the game. I can only make sense of the various scenes by what I see with my eyes. Violett does not attempt to enrich that with any further explanation, for example items that are picked up cannot be examined closer nor do they have labels. I've come across a few things that I have no idea what they are let alone what to use them for. Violett is also a little helpless when trying something that isn't valid. Just a shrug with little indication (in most cases) as to why it is not valid. It reminds me of those old school Text Adventures that had the default response ""I can't do that"". I'm never sure if it's because it is impossible in the game or I haven't satisfied all the prerequisites.It must be noted that the controls are simplistic but unfortunately a tad clunky. They feel as they've been designed with a touch device in mind. I'm playing with a keyboard and mouse so that may be why.I can't not recommend this game as it certainly does have merit, it's reasonably executed and it has generated a lot of eager discussion and favourable comments in the forum, but for me I don't think I have the will to progress much further. If you enjoy puzzle based games then you may get something out of Violett but mileage will vary."
