,Recommended,257830,8106591,"Posted: 18 December, 2013",all,Ucchedavāda,"After having finished Violett, I am in two minds about whether or not to recommend it, so in the end I've chosen to recommend it, but with some (significant) caveats.In Violett, you'll guide the titular protagonist through a beautifully rendered fantasy land, which is peopled with strange creatures, and reminiscent of Alice in Wonderland. While doing so, you'll be enjoying excellent background music, which is also included with the game as MP3s. Violett is a point-and-click adventure game, with elements of a hidden-object game. Not only are many objects with which you need to interact hidden, but there are also collectible ""orbs"" which (as far as I can tell) only earn you an achievement if you bother to collect them, in addition to diary pages which flesh out the mythology behind the fantastical creatures you encounter. The player is thus rewarded for carefully inspecting each landscape and interacting with everything. Overall, I found the puzzles to be pretty reasonable, though there are some needlessly repeated actions in a few cases.Similarly to Journey of a Roach, the game does not include actual spoken dialogue (the words spoken are gibberish), but instead relies on pictographs to convey meaning. Mostly, this works pretty well, but in a couple of cases I found it hard to decipher the meaning of the pictograph, until I had inadvertently stumbled upon part of the solution to the puzzle at hand.However, that leads me to the issues I have with this game, the main issue being the control scheme. Actions typically involve either clicking on stuff (which works well), or dragging items from the inventory or from one place to another on the current screen. Unfortunately, it can be rather difficult to drag stuff, and I even had difficulty with something as simple as dragging items out of my inventory. This was a constant source of frustration, and the only positive I can say with regards to this control-scheme, is that the game will tell you when you have to interact with an object by dragging it.Secondly, the game is rather buggy at this point, with one patch just released. Several times, Violett would be stuck in a ""can't do that"" animation loop, and I was forced to quit to the main menu and resume the game to continue. Even worse, one puzzle forced me to repeatedly reload, so that it would reset to a state where I could exit it from my current position (the elevator puzzle). Similarly, I could not interact with a couple of items (plant-bulbs), even though I had obtained the prerequisites to do so, and missed a couple of diary pages due to this.Thirdly, the actual plot is very sparse (due in part to the lack of dialogue), and the ending came as a bit of a surprise.However, if you are willing to put up with these issues, then I'll gladly recommend trying out Violett."
