,Not Recommended,257830,16153179,"Posted: 3 June, 2015",all,HimeJezabel,"Well. The game's art is great and so is the music. For some reason the main character is the worst looking thing in the game.Violett moves to a spooky house in the country with her parents. She seems unhappy about it. In her room she discovers a magical amulet in a mouse hole. This takes her to a magical world of fairies and bugs. Think Coraline with a lighter tone and more colours.This game is incredibly frustrating in many ways. Some times it's hard to know where you can walk because of the layout of the map. Some times this is solved by the creators by putting an arrow in the landscape, so I guess they realised their error and fixed it an easy way. The clickables sometimes changes the mousecursor to an 'available action' hand, some times not.As a completelist I haven't been this frustrated about collectibles since as long as I can remember. The orbs are sometimes easy to spot, some times can only been seen from certain angles, sometimes actually invisible. Some of the hidden places are the same way; some easy to spot some you will only see in a guide.If you miss the orbs or diary page in the first room, there is no way to go back and you'll have to start a new game if you want the completist achievements. There is also a bug that happens sometimes where Violett will get stuck for no reason and you'll have to exit and load game to fix it. As far as I can tell from internet searches and guides I collected all the diary pages needed for the achievement, yet I did not get it.The voiceacting. I don't mind gibberish-language games, but some of the voices in this game is just plain annoying. And ofcourse the one you'll hear the most, Violett, is the most annoying of them all. The sound Violett makes when she tells you she can't do whatever action you tried to make her do, is one of the most annoying sounds ever and you feel severely punished for not clicking everything perfectly. Add to this that it's impossible to turn off the sound effects; you can only turn it down to level 1/10. All of this makes it 100% necessary to use a guide at all times, which always makes the game less fun.Violett collects pages from her uncle's diary throughout the game, but nothing is told by the game of who the uncle is, how and why he was in the same world Violett discovered.I bought this on 85% off and suffered 10 hours of frustration as I didn't want it to drag down my achievement collection % and always hoping that the game would improve. Turns out I still can't complete everything. Not worth."
76561198027364206,Recommended,257830,8715003,"Posted: 15 January, 2014",all,ikillomega,"If you are a fan of classic point-and-click adventure games, then Violett will satisfy.  It's a traditional game with a simple structure and puzzles that are challenging without being overly frustrating.  In an era of revitalizations of classic genres and reboots of the great titles of yesterday, Violett is a combination of modern art design, and genre-traditional gamepay.  The little touches in level design and the way the story is silently told make this another entry in the recent trend of games that has been creating artistic statement in the narrative by embedding the story in the gameplay.  Violett is a lovely new entry in a series of titles that are taking gaming into a new more artistically-mature direction alongside games like Limbo, Braid and, more recently, Gone Home and The Stanley Parable."
