76561198054652914,Recommended,257830,29912468,Posted: 13 February,all,Murkg,"Cute little fairy-tale point-and-click with lots of character and atmosphere, plagued by lackluster design, time-wasting mechanics, and a few bugs. Definitely worth a playthrough for its charm and worth the 10 bucks for the soundtrack alone.[Story]In this game you play a disenfranchised teenage girl who gets shrunk down to bug size and teleported into a magical world ruled by an evil spider (although we only really have the game's word for it).[Puzzles/game design]The puzzles are pretty much self-contained in each room and most of them can be figured out with some logic. The ones that can't be figured out by logic can be either figured out with some patient trial-and-error, or by using the pretty well designed hint system. The puzzles are pretty straightforward and fairly simple, but they are more logical and less dumb than those of, for instance, Deponia, or Broken Age. There are some unnecessarily long animations and walking sequences that cannot be skipped and sometimes have to be repeated as part of a puzzle. This felt very much like padding and is the game's worst sin.[Bugs]The game is plagued by the occasional bug, for instance Violett sometimes simply won't enter a door you click on or interact with an object. This can be solved by a simple save and quit. I was able to play the game from beginning to end without much of a hitch, load-times are fast. I didn't mind it and since the game is clearly on an indy budget it can be forgiven.[Art design and atmosphere]The main appeal of this game is its charm. It feels like a somewhat dark fairy-tale with a good dose of humor. The art-pieces are very compelling, varied, and invoke a sense of wonder. It is well drawn and animated. The world is densely populated with a variety of cute and amusing creatures. For instance, there are a hookah smoking caterpillar and a tuxedo wearing cockroach. Throughout the world are strewn pages of ""uncle's bestiary"" which make for a compelling read and I found myself going out of my way to find and read them all, even though I usually don't have the patience to read anything, especially not when playing a game. Some puzzles feel a little like a Rube-Goldberg machine, adding to the charm.[Sound]The star of the show is the soundtrack, which is absolutely magical. The sound design (done by the composer of the music as well) is strong and really helps solidify the already charming atmosphere created by the visual art pieces and animations.[Bottom line]The game gets way more flack than it deserves. The puzzles are more logical and less mindless than those of the average point-and-click adventure. The bugs are obnoxious but not game-breaking as are the sometimes overlong animations. It has more charm and more refined humor than most point-and-clicks out there and you will be listening to the soundtrack non-stop for days. I might replay this game from the start just to take in the atmosphere again."
,Recommended,257830,33754620,Posted: 23 July,all,mysticmynstrel,I loved this game! I can't wait for the developers to make more point and click puzzle games like this.
